Windows: fix update interval

According to the Qt docs, the updateInterval == 0 means that the system
will provide the positioning updates as often as necessary.
In practice that means that some system-specific value should be
selected.
The windows backend implementation has a comment that states that zero
update interval leads to an error. That is, indeed, the case - after
setting IGeolocator::ReportInterval = 0, it is impossible to install
the PositionChanged callback.
However, the logic right below the comment still allowed to set the
interval to 0.
Fix it by using the minimumUpdateInterval() in such case.

Amends 9307404d2dcb0b53d0dfcad6c28677cc2aba4a12.

Pick-to: 6.7 6.6 6.5 6.2
Change-Id: I7cefb7f7a539891be65e2ac8b94b224d4c01d39a
Reviewed-by: Oliver Wolff <oliver.wolff@qt.io>

Windows: fix a potential crash when requesting a single update

The startHandler() method can set an error and return false in case
of an error.
Suppose that the client code decides to replace the plugin in case of
an error (that's exactly what the SatelliteInfo example does).
Then the following scenario is possible:
* QGeoPositionInfoSourceWinRT::requestUpdate() is called
* It calls startHandler(), which returns false and sets an error
* The client code handles the error and decides to use another backend
* During the backend change, the current windows backend is deleted...
* ... and we're back in QGeoPositionInfoSourceWinRT::requestUpdate(),
  trying to dereference the already-removed d_ptr.

Fix the issue by making sure that we do not do anything if
startHandler() returns false.

Fixes: QTBUG-119477

Windows backend: cleanup WinRT usage

Qt 6 does not support WinRT as a separate platform.
qeventdispatcher_winrt_p.h was removed in 6.0 and runOnXamlThread()
calls make no sense.

Clean up the code to get rid of stale ifdefs and method calls.
Replace all runOnXamlThread() calls with Immediately Invokable Lambda
Expressions (IILE) to minimize the diff.

Pick the changes to all LTS branches to simplify further bugfixing.

Android: allow to convert altitude to MSL on Android 14 and later

[ChangeLog][QGeoPositionInfo][Android] Intoroduce a plugin parameter
that allows to convert the altitude from WGS84 to MSL. This parameter
works only on Android 14 and later. By default the altitude is still
returned in WGS84 format for backwards compatibility.

Android is known to report the altitude in WGS84, which is different
from other QtPositioning backends.
Android 14 introduces a new AltitudeConverter class, which allows
to add an MSL altitude to the Location object.

This patch adds a plugin-specific parameter called `useMslAltitude`.
The default value is false to preserve the old behavior. If the value
is set to true, and an Android version >= 14 is used, position requests
will return the altitude in MSL format.

It also adds documentation for the android plugin.

Fixes: QTBUG-106049

Update poly2tri third-party component

A pull-request #117 [1] has recently been merged into the master
branch.

It contains two fixes:
- updated logic of Sweep::LargeHole_DontFill()
- updated logic of operator!=(const Point &, const Point &)

The first fix introduces a new const method which is calling
a non-const method. It also passes the parameters incorrectly.
This results in the build errors. As a result, we cannot apply this
fix to our code.

The second fix is fine, so integrate it.

For the first fix I created a follow-up pull-request #120 [2]. Once
it is merged, we can integrate this change as well.

Add a "Version" field to qt_attribution.json and mention the
current upstream commit hash. Previously there was no way to figure
out an actual version of the library that was used.

[1]: https://github.com/greenm01/poly2tri/pull/117
[2]: https://github.com/greenm01/poly2tri/pull/120
